1 Bayesian Networks: Discrete Case Notebook

Graphical Representation

library(bnlearn)

We first create a DAG with one node for each of the variables and no arcs

dag <- empty.graph(nodes = c("A", "S", "E", "O", "R", "T"))
dag

  Random/Generated Bayesian network

  model:
   [A][S][E][O][R][T] 
  nodes:                                 6 
  arcs:                                  0 
    undirected arcs:                     0 
    directed arcs:                       0 
  average markov blanket size:           0.00 
  average neighbourhood size:            0.00 
  average branching factor:              0.00 

  generation algorithm:                  Empty

Next, we add the arcs that encode the direct dependencies between the variables in the survey. Age and Sex are not influenced by any other variables. But both have a direct influence on Education. Similarlly, Sex also influences Education. In turn, Education influences both Occupation and Residence. Finally, the preferred menas of transport are directly influenced by both Occupation and Residence.

dag <- set.arc(dag, from = "A", to = "E")
dag <- set.arc(dag, from = "S", to = "E")
dag <- set.arc(dag, from = "E", to = "R")
dag <- set.arc(dag, from = "E", to = "O")
dag <- set.arc(dag, from = "O", to = "T")
dag <- set.arc(dag, from = "R", to = "T")
dag

  Random/Generated Bayesian network

  model:
   [A][S][E|A:S][O|E][R|E][T|O:R] 
  nodes:                                 6 
  arcs:                                  6 
    undirected arcs:                     0 
    directed arcs:                       6 
  average markov blanket size:           2.67 
  average neighbourhood size:            2.00 
  average branching factor:              1.00 

  generation algorithm:                  Empty 
print(modelstring(dag))
[1] "[A][S][E|A:S][O|E][R|E][T|O:R]"
print(nodes(dag))
[1] "A" "S" "E" "O" "R" "T"
print(arcs(dag))
     from to 
[1,] "A"  "E"
[2,] "S"  "E"
[3,] "E"  "R"
[4,] "E"  "O"
[5,] "O"  "T"
[6,] "R"  "T"
graphviz.plot(dag)

dag2 <- empty.graph(nodes = c("A", "S", "E", "O", "R", "T"))
arc.set <- matrix(c("A", "E",
                    "S", "E",
                    "E", "O",
                    "E", "R",
                    "O", "T",
                    "R", "T"),
                  byrow = TRUE, ncol = 2,
                  dimnames = list(NULL, c("from", "to")))
arcs(dag2) <- arc.set
all.equal(dag, dag2)
[1] TRUE

Probabilisitc Representation

A.lv <- c("young", "adult", "old")
S.lv <- c("M", "F")
E.lv <- c("high", "uni")
O.lv <- c("emp", "self")
R.lv <- c("small", "big")
T.lv <- c("car", "train", "other")

One Dimensional Tables

A.prob <- array(c(0.30, 0.50, 0.20), dim = 3,
                dimnames = list(A = A.lv))
print(A.prob)
A
young adult   old 
  0.3   0.5   0.2 
S.prob <- array(c(0.60, 0.40), dim = 2,
                dimnames = list(S = S.lv))
print(S.prob)
S
  M   F 
0.6 0.4

Two Dimensional Tables

O.prob <- array(c(0.96, 0.04, 0.92, 0.08), dim = c(2, 2),
                dimnames = list(O = O.lv, E = E.lv))
R.prob <- array(c(0.25, 0.75, 0.20, 0.80), dim = c(2, 2),
                dimnames = list(R = R.lv, E = E.lv))

# list of local distributions 
cpt <- list(A = A.prob, S = S.prob, E = E.prob, 
            O = O.prob, R = R.prob, T = T.prob)

# combine DAG with cpt
bn <- custom.fit(dag, cpt)
print(nparams(bn))

using a set of custom parameters specified by the user.

## Bayesian Estimates

The estimated posterior probabilities are computed from a uniform prior
over each conditional probability table.

iss -\> imaginary sample size or equivalent sample size - determines how
much weight is assigned to the prior distribution compared to the data
when computing. \# the posterior.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuXG5ibl9iYXllcyA8LSBibi5maXQoZGFnMiwgZGF0YSA9IHN1cnZleSwgbWV0aG9kID0gXFxiYXllc1xcLCBpc3M9MTApIFxucHJpbnQoYm5fYmF5ZXMkTylcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
```r

bn_bayes <- bn.fit(dag2, data = survey, method = \bayes\, iss=10) 
print(bn_bayes$O)

Increasing the value of iss makes the posterior distribution more and
more flat, pushing it towards the uniform distribution used as the
prior.

# Learning the DAG Structure: Tests and Scores

the DAG of the survey we are using as an example suggests that train
fares should be adjusted (to maximise profit) on the basis of Occupation
and Residence alone.

## Conditional Independence Tests

Conditional independence tests focus on the presence of individual arcs.
Since each arc encodes a probabilistic dependence, conditional
independence tests can be used to assess whether that probabilistic
dependence is supported by the data. If the null hypothesis (of
conditional independence) is rejected, the arc can be considered for
inclusion in the DAG.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuIyBkZWdyZXNzIG9mIGZyZWVkb21cbihubGV2ZWxzKHN1cnZleVssIFxcVFxcXSkgLSAxKSAqIChubGV2ZWxzKHN1cnZleVssIFxcRVxcXSkgLSAxKSAqXG4rIChubGV2ZWxzKHN1cnZleVssIFxcT1xcXSkgKiBubGV2ZWxzKHN1cnZleVssIFxcUlxcXSkpXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
# degress of freedom
(nlevels(survey[, \T\]) - 1) * (nlevels(survey[, \E\]) - 1) *
+ (nlevels(survey[, \O\]) * nlevels(survey[, \R\]))

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-output-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiWzFdIDhcbiJ9 -->

[1] 8




<!-- rnb-output-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


## ci.test implements both log-likelihood ratio $G^2$ and Pearson's $X^2$


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuIyBsb2ctbGlrZWxpaG9vZCByYXRpbyBHXjJcbmNpLnRlc3QoXG4gIFxcVFxcLCBcXEVcXCwgYyhcXE9cXCwgXFxSXFwpLCB0ZXN0ID0gXFxtaVxcLCBkYXRhID0gc3VydmV5XG4pXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
# log-likelihood ratio G^2
ci.test(
  \T\, \E\, c(\O\, \R\), test = \mi\, data = survey
)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-output-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiXG5cdE11dHVhbCBJbmZvcm1hdGlvbiAoZGlzYy4pXG5cbmRhdGE6ICBUIH4gRSB8IE8gKyBSXG5taSA9IDkuODgzNiwgZGYgPSA4LCBwLXZhbHVlID0gMC4yNzMzXG5hbHRlcm5hdGl2ZSBoeXBvdGhlc2lzOiB0cnVlIHZhbHVlIGlzIGdyZWF0ZXIgdGhhbiAwXG4ifQ== -->

Mutual Information (disc.)

data: T ~ E | O + R mi = 9.8836, df = 8, p-value = 0.2733 alternative hypothesis: true value is greater than 0




<!-- rnb-output-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->



<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuY2kudGVzdChcbiAgXFxUXFwsIFxcRVxcLCBjKFxcT1xcLCBcXFJcXCksIHRlc3QgPSBcXHgyXFwsIGRhdGEgPSBzdXJ2ZXlcbilcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
```r
ci.test(
  \T\, \E\, c(\O\, \R\), test = \x2\, data = survey
)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-output-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiXG5cdFBlYXJzb24ncyBYXjJcblxuZGF0YTogIFQgfiBFIHwgTyArIFJcbngyID0gOC4yMzc1LCBkZiA9IDgsIHAtdmFsdWUgPSAwLjQxMDZcbmFsdGVybmF0aXZlIGh5cG90aGVzaXM6IHRydWUgdmFsdWUgaXMgZ3JlYXRlciB0aGFuIDBcbiJ9 -->

Pearson's X^2

data: T ~ E | O + R x2 = 8.2375, df = 8, p-value = 0.4106 alternative hypothesis: true value is greater than 0




<!-- rnb-output-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


Both tests return very large p-values indicating that the dependence
between E and T is not supported by the data. Next, we can check whether
one of the arcs in the DAG should be removed because the dependence
relationship is not suuported by the data. We check O to T.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuY2kudGVzdChcbiAgXFxUXFwsIFxcT1xcLCBcXFJcXCwgdGVzdCA9IFxceDJcXCwgZGF0YSA9IHN1cnZleVxuKVxuYGBgXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
```r
ci.test(
  \T\, \O\, \R\, test = \x2\, data = survey
)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-output-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiXG5cdFBlYXJzb24ncyBYXjJcblxuZGF0YTogIFQgfiBPIHwgUlxueDIgPSAzLjc5ODgsIGRmID0gNCwgcC12YWx1ZSA9IDAuNDMzOVxuYWx0ZXJuYXRpdmUgaHlwb3RoZXNpczogdHJ1ZSB2YWx1ZSBpcyBncmVhdGVyIHRoYW4gMFxuIn0= -->

Pearson's X^2

data: T ~ O | R x2 = 3.7988, df = 4, p-value = 0.4339 alternative hypothesis: true value is greater than 0




<!-- rnb-output-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->



<!-- rnb-text-end -->

<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


We can check the strength of all arcs using arc.strength. arc.strength
measures the strength of the probabilistic dependence by removing each
arc from the graph and quantifying the change with some probabilistic
criterion. Strength here is p-value. We see that all arcs are well
supported by the data except O to T.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuYXJjLnN0cmVuZ3RoKFxuICBkYWcsIGRhdGEgPSBzdXJ2ZXksIGNyaXRlcmlvbiA9IFxceDJcXFxuKVxuYGBgXG5gYGAifQ== -->

## Network Scores

Network scores consider the whole DAG. They are goodness-of-fit
statistics measuring how well the DAG fits the dependence structure of
the data. There are two network scores we consider: 1. Bayesian
Information Criterion (BIC) 2. Bayesian Dirichlet equivalent form (BDe)


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuc2NvcmUoZGFnLCBkYXRhID0gc3VydmV5LCB0eXBlID0gJ2JpYycpXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
score(dag, data = survey, type = 'bic')

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-output-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiWzFdIC0yMDEyLjY4N1xuIn0= -->

[1] -2012.687




<!-- rnb-output-end -->

<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuIyBsb2cgQmRlXG5zY29yZShkYWcsIGRhdGEgPSBzdXJ2ZXksIHR5cGUgPSAnYmRlJywgaXNzID0gMTApXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
# log Bde
score(dag, data = survey, type = 'bde', iss = 10)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

## Learning the DAG

There are several algorithms that tackle the task of learning the DAG
from the data. \### Hill Climbing Starts a DAG with no arcs and then
adds, removes, and reverses one arc at at time and picks the change that
increase the score the most.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxubGVhcm5lZCA8LSBoYyhzdXJ2ZXkpXG5tb2RlbHN0cmluZyhsZWFybmVkKVxuYGBgXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
```r
learned <- hc(survey)
modelstring(learned)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-output-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiWzFdIFxcW1JdW0V8Ul1bVHxSXVtBfEVdW098RV1bU3xFXVxcXG4ifQ== -->

[1] [R][E|R][T|R][A|E][O|E][S|E]




<!-- rnb-output-end -->

<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuc2NvcmUobGVhcm5lZCwgZGF0YSA9IHN1cnZleSwgdHlwZSA9IFxcYmljXFwpXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
score(learned, data = survey, type = \bic\)

# Using Discrete BNs

We say that two variables **X** and **Y** are conditionally independent
or *d-separated* given **Z** if there are no arcs connecting them that
are not blocked by the conditioning variable.

Note: if all paths between **X** and **Y** are blocked, we say they are
conditionally independent. The converse is not necessarily true. Not all
conditional independence relationships are reflected on a graph


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuZHNlcChkYWcsIHggPSBcXFNcXCwgeSA9IFxcUlxcKSAjIGZhbHNlIHdoZW4gbm90IGNvbmRpdGlvbmVkIG9uIEVcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
```r
dsep(dag, x = \S\, y = \R\) # false when not conditioned on E

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-output-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiWzFdIEZBTFNFXG4ifQ== -->

[1] FALSE




<!-- rnb-output-end -->

<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuZHNlcChkYWcsIHggPSBcXE9cXCwgeSA9IFxcUlxcKVxuYGBgXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
```r
dsep(dag, x = \O\, y = \R\)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-output-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiWzFdIEZBTFNFXG4ifQ== -->

[1] FALSE




<!-- rnb-output-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->

## Fundamental Connections

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxucGF0aC5leGlzdHMoZGFnLCBmcm9tID0gXFxTXFwsIHRvID0gXFxSXFwpIFxuYGBgXG5gYGAifQ== -->

path.exists(dag, from = \S\, to = \R\)

[1] TRUE




<!-- rnb-output-end -->

<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuIyBzZXJpYWwgY29ubmVjdGlvblxuZHNlcChkYWcsIHggPSBcXFNcXCwgeSA9IFxcUlxcLCB6ID0gXFxFXFwpICMgdHJ1ZSB3aGVuIGNvbmRpdGlvbmVkIG9uIEVcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

# serial connection
dsep(dag, x = \S\, y = \R\, z = \E\) # true when conditioned on E

dsep(dag, x = \O\, y = \R\, z = \E\) # true when conditioned on E

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-output-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiWzFdIFRSVUVcbiJ9 -->

[1] TRUE

# convergent connection
dsep(dag, x = \A\, y = \S\, z = \E\)

### Convergent connection
Conditioning on particular node can also make other nodes dependent when they are
marginally independent

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuIyBjb252ZXJnZW50IGNvbm5lY3Rpb25cbmRzZXAoZGFnLCB4ID0gXFxBXFwsIHkgPSBcXFNcXClcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
```r
# convergent connection
dsep(dag, x = \A\, y = \S\)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-output-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiWzFdIFRSVUVcbiJ9 -->

[1] TRUE




<!-- rnb-output-end -->

<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuZHNlcChkYWcsIHggPSBcXEFcXCwgeSA9IFxcU1xcLCB6ID0gXFxFXFwpXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
dsep(dag, x = \A\, y = \S\, z = \E\)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

## Using Conditonal Probability Tables
### Exact Inference

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->

```r
library(gRain)

# as.grain creates the junction tree
# compile builds the probability table of the junction tree
junction <- compile(as.grain(bn))

<!-- rnb-text-begin -->

For example, we may be interested in the attitudes of women towards car
and train use compared to the whole survey sample


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuIyBjb3Jyc3BvbmRzIHRvIFAoVClcbnF1ZXJ5Z3JhaW4oanVuY3Rpb24sIG5vZGVzID0gXFxUXFwpJFRcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
```r
# corrsponds to P(T)
querygrain(junction, nodes = \T\)$T

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-output-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiVFxuICAgICAgY2FyICAgICB0cmFpbiAgICAgb3RoZXIgXG4wLjU2MTgzNDAgMC4yODA4NTczIDAuMTU3MzA4OCBcbiJ9 -->

T car train other 0.5618340 0.2808573 0.1573088




<!-- rnb-output-end -->

<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuanNleCA8LSBzZXRFdmlkZW5jZShcbiAganVuY3Rpb24sIFxuICBub2RlcyA9IFxcU1xcLFxuICBzdGF0ZXMgPSBcXEZcXFxuKVxuIyBjb3JyZXNwb25kcyB0byBQKFQgfCBTID0gRilcbnF1ZXJ5Z3JhaW4oanNleCwgbm9kZXMgPSBcXFRcXCkkVFxuYGBgXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
```r
jsex <- setEvidence(
  junction, 
  nodes = \S\,
  states = \F\
)
# corresponds to P(T | S = F)
querygrain(jsex, nodes = \T\)$T

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-output-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiVFxuICAgICAgY2FyICAgICB0cmFpbiAgICAgb3RoZXIgXG4wLjU2MjA1NzcgMC4yODA2MTQ0IDAuMTU3MzI4MCBcbiJ9 -->

T car train other 0.5620577 0.2806144 0.1573280




<!-- rnb-output-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->

There is no real difference in probabilities derived from the junction 
before and after inputting evidence. This suggests women show about the 
same preference towards car, train, and other, as the survey as a whole.

Another interesting question is how living in a small city affects car and
train use, that is P(T | R = small). We can conjecture that people working
in cities often live in neighboring towns and commute to their workplaces.
This forces them to travel mostly by car or train and less so by other 
means of transporation like bicycles or bus. 

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuanJlcyA8LSBzZXRFdmlkZW5jZShcbiAganVuY3Rpb24sIFxuICBub2RlcyA9IFxcUlxcLFxuICBzdGF0ZXMgPSBcXHNtYWxsXFxcbilcbnF1ZXJ5Z3JhaW4oanJlcywgbm9kZXMgPSBcXFRcXCkkVFxuYGBgXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
```r
jres <- setEvidence(
  junction, 
  nodes = \R\,
  states = \small\
)
querygrain(jres, nodes = \T\)$T

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-output-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiVFxuICAgICAgIGNhciAgICAgIHRyYWluICAgICAgb3RoZXIgXG4wLjQ4Mzg4Njc1IDAuNDE3MDg0OTQgMC4wOTkwMjgzMSBcbiJ9 -->

T car train other 0.48388675 0.41708494 0.09902831




<!-- rnb-output-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->

We see that this reasoning is supported by the BN. Combined probabilty 
of car and train is at 90% (for people living in small cities.)

Conditional probability queries can be used to determine conditional independence. Consider again the relationship between S and T, this 
time conditioning on E = high. That is we want P(S, T | E = high).

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuamVkdSA8LSBzZXRFdmlkZW5jZShcbiAganVuY3Rpb24sXG4gIG5vZGVzID0gXFxFXFwsXG4gIHN0YXRlcyA9IFxcaGlnaFxcXG4pXG5TeFQuY3B0IDwtcXVlcnlncmFpbihqdW5jdGlvbiwgbm9kZXMgPSBjKFxcU1xcLCBcXFRcXCksIHR5cGUgPSBcXGpvaW50XFwpXG5TeFQuY3B0XG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
jedu <- setEvidence(
  junction,
  nodes = \E\,
  states = \high\
)
SxT.cpt <-querygrain(junction, nodes = c(\S\, \T\), type = \joint\)
SxT.cpt

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

```r
```r
querygrain(junction, nodes = c(\S\, \T\), type =\marginal\)

<!-- rnb-output-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiJFNcblNcbiAgTSAgIEYgXG4wLjYgMC40IFxuXG4kVFxuVFxuICAgICAgY2FyICAgICB0cmFpbiAgICAgb3RoZXIgXG4wLjU2MTgzNDAgMC4yODA4NTczIDAuMTU3MzA4OCBcbiJ9 -->

$T T car train other 0.5618340 0.2808573 0.1573088

<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuIyBQKFN8VCA9IHQsIEUgPSBoaWdoKVxucXVlcnlncmFpbihqdW5jdGlvbiwgbm9kZXMgPSBjKFxcU1xcLCBcXFRcXCksIHR5cGUgPVxcY29uZGl0aW9uYWxcXClcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
```r
# P(S|T = t, E = high)
querygrain(junction, nodes = c(\S\, \T\), type =\conditional\)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-output-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiICAgVFxuUyAgICAgICAgIGNhciAgICAgdHJhaW4gICAgIG90aGVyXG4gIE0gMC41OTk4NDA3IDAuNjAwMzQ1OSAwLjU5OTk1MTJcbiAgRiAwLjQwMDE1OTMgMC4zOTk2NTQxIDAuNDAwMDQ4OFxuIn0= -->

T S car train other M 0.5998407 0.6003459 0.5999512 F 0.4001593 0.3996541 0.4000488




<!-- rnb-output-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->

We note that all the conditional probabilities P(S = M| T= t, E = high) are virtually the same regardless of T - the same when S = F. This suggests that S and T are conditionally independent on E. That is, knowing the sex of the person is not informative of their travel preferences when we know their Education. We can also check this with graphical separation.

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuZHNlcChibiwgeCA9IFxcU1xcLCB5ID0gXFxUXFwsIHogPSBcXEVcXClcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
```r
dsep(bn, x = \S\, y = \T\, z = \E\)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-output-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiWzFdIFRSVUVcbiJ9 -->

[1] TRUE




<!-- rnb-output-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->

Another way of confirming connditional independence is to use the joint distribution and perform a Pearsons $X^2$ test for independence. First, we need to multiply the cpt by the sample size to convert conditional probability into contingency tables.

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuU3hULmN0ID0gU3hULmNwdCAqIG5yb3coc3VydmV5KVxuY2hpc3EudGVzdChTeFQuY3QpXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
SxT.ct = SxT.cpt * nrow(survey)
chisq.test(SxT.ct)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-output-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiXG5cdFBlYXJzb24ncyBDaGktc3F1YXJlZCB0ZXN0XG5cbmRhdGE6ICBTeFQuY3Rcblgtc3F1YXJlZCA9IDAuMDAwMTAwNDksIGRmID0gMiwgcC12YWx1ZSA9IDAuOTk5OVxuIn0= -->

Pearson's Chi-squared test

data: SxT.ct X-squared = 0.00010049, df = 2, p-value = 0.9999




<!-- rnb-output-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->

### Approximate Inference
In this approach we use Monte Carlo simulations to randomly generate
observations from the BN and use these observations to approximate the 
conditional probabilities we are interested in.

For Discrete BNs we can use rejection sampling.

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuIyByYW5kb20gc2FtcGxpbmdcbiMgcmV0dXJuIHRoZSBwcm9iYWJpbGl0eSBvZiBhIHNwZWNpZmljIGV2ZW50IGdpdmVuIHNvbWUgZXZpZGVuY2VcbmNwcXVlcnkoXG4gIGJuLFxuICBldmVudCA9IChTID09IFxcTVxcKSAmIChUID09IFxcY2FyXFwpLFxuICBldmlkZW5jZSA9IChFID09IFxcaGlnaFxcKSxcbiAgbiA9IDEwXjYgICMgbnVtIG9mIHJhbmRvbSBvYnNlcnZhdGlvbnMsIGluY3JlYXNlIHRvIGltcHJvdmUgYXBwcnhcbilcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
```r
# random sampling
# return the probability of a specific event given some evidence
cpquery(
  bn,
  event = (S == \M\) & (T == \car\),
  evidence = (E == \high\),
  n = 10^6  # num of random observations, increase to improve apprx
)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-output-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiWzFdIDAuMzQxOTg4N1xuIn0= -->

[1] 0.3419887




<!-- rnb-output-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->

Increasing precision by increasing n has several drawbacks - longer query times and the precision may still be low if the probability of the evidence is low. A better approach is *likelihood weighting* - where random observations generated match the evidence and re-weights them appropriately when computing the conditional probability query. 

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuY3BxdWVyeShibiwgXG4gICAgICAgIGV2ZW50ID0gKFMgPT0gXFxNXFwpICYgKFQgPT0gXFxjYXJcXCksXG4gICAgICAgIGV2aWRlbmNlID0gbGlzdChFID0gXFxoaWdoXFwpLCBcbiAgICAgICAgbWV0aG9kID0gXFxsd1xcXG4pXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
cpquery(bn, 
        event = (S == \M\) & (T == \car\),
        evidence = list(E = \high\), 
        method = \lw\
)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-output-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiWzFdIDAuMzUxNTY4N1xuIn0= -->

[1] 0.3515687




<!-- rnb-output-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuY3BxdWVyeShcbiAgYm4sXG4gIGV2ZW50ID0gKFMgPT0gXFxNXFwpICYgKFQgPT0gXFxjYXJcXCksXG4gIGV2aWRlbmNlID0gKChBID09IFxceW91bmdcXCkgJiAoRSA9PSBcXHVuaVxcKSB8IChBID09IFxcYWR1bHRcXCkpXG4pXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
cpquery(
  bn,
  event = (S == \M\) & (T == \car\),
  evidence = ((A == \young\) & (E == \uni\) | (A == \adult\))
)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-output-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiWzFdIDAuMzM0Njk2N1xuIn0= -->

[1] 0.3346967




<!-- rnb-output-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->

The implementation of likelihood weighting in cpquery is not flexible enough to compute a query with composite evidence like the above; in that respect it shares the same limitations as the functions in the
gRain package.

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuU3hUIDwtIGNwZGlzdChcbiAgYm4sXG4gIG5vZGVzID0gYyhcXFNcXCwgXFxUXFwpLFxuICBldmlkZW5jZSA9IChFID09IFxcaGlnaFxcKVxuKVxuaGVhZChTeFQpXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
SxT <- cpdist(
  bn,
  nodes = c(\S\, \T\),
  evidence = (E == \high\)
)
head(SxT)

library(Rgraphviz)
# rendering arcs
edgeRenderInfo(pp) <-
  list(col = c(\S~E\ = \red\, \E~R\ = \black\),
       lwd = c(\S~E\ = 3, \E~R\ = 5))

# highlighting nodes
nodeRenderInfo(pp) <- list(
  col = c(\S\ = \blue\, \E\ = \black\, \R\ = \black\),
  textCol = c(\S\ = \black\, \E\ = \purple\, \R\ = \black\),
  fill = c(\E\ = \grey\)
)
renderGraph(pp)

library(lattice)

barchart(
  Travel ~ Prob | Evidence, data = distr,
  layout = c(3, 1), xlab = \probability\,
  scales = list(alternating = 1, tck = c(1, 0)),
  strip = strip.custom(
    factor.levels =c(expression(Pr(T)),
                     expression(Pr({T} * \ | \ * {S == F})),
                     expression(Pr({T} * \ | \ * {R == small})))),
  panel = function(...) {
    panel.barchart(...)
    panel.grid(h = 0, v = -1)
}
)

# set the nodes
my_dag <- empty.graph(nodes = c(\A\, \S\, \E\, \O\, \R\, \T\))

# set arcs
arc_matrix <- matrix(c(\A\, \E\,
                    \S\, \E\,
                    \E\, \O\,
                    \E\, \R\,
                    \O\, \T\,
                    \R\, \T\),
                  byrow = TRUE, ncol = 2,
                  dimnames = list(NULL, c(\from\, \to\)))
arcs(my_dag) <- arc_matrix

my_dag
